	<h2>Peh Is for Parsee</h2>

	<p class="first">Peh hardly seems a letter of its own. Its shapes (ship&rsquo;s stern, notch or plate) are all the shapes of Ba. All you have, if you want to tell them apart, are dots. The distinction from the sound of Ba isn&rsquo;t so big either. Ba is voiced, Peh just our P, a puff of air.</p>
	
	<p>The three dots hang below the line in an equilateral triangle, pointing downward, a heavier load than Ba&rsquo;s single dot, and as always, each dot is a square the thickness of the reed&rsquo;s edge tilted 45 degrees, clustering together like tiles. Anyway, that&rsquo;s what it looks like drawn by a calligrapher. Formed with a pencil or a ballpoint pen, by one of us, writing in a hurry, the three dots may become three simple points, or they may be stylized as a circle. It is still clearly a form of Ba.</p>
	
	<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/pa-2.png" width="250" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>

	<p>If Alif and Ba have pedigrees stretching back to the edge of pre-history, still showing traces of ox and house, with Peh we enter recorded history, sort of. The inventor thought to have stepped in to fill the alphabetical gap is a figure named Khw&acirc;jeh Ab&ucirc;&rsquo;l-&lsquo; l, or perhaps Ab&ucirc;&rsquo;l-M&acirc;l. (I&rsquo;ve seen both.) He no doubt had dates of birth and death, but I can&rsquo;t locate them. (10th century?) He is credited with the invention of adding the extra two dots to represent the unvoiced B, or P.</p>
	
	<p>Altogether there are four such sounds, unavailable in the standard Arabic alphabet: P, Zh (the sound of the French J in <em>jour</em> or <em>bijou</em>), Ch as in &ldquo;change,&rdquo; &ldquo;cello,&rdquo; or &ldquo;ciao,&rdquo; and hard G as in &ldquo;Google&rdquo; or  &ldquo;ganja.&rdquo; Khw&acirc;jeh Ab&ucirc;&rsquo;l-&lsquo;&acirc;l, or perhaps Ab&ucirc;&rsquo;l-M&acirc;l, devised three altogether: P, Zh and Ch (all by using three dots). G is a different story.</p>

	<p>His improvisations brought the number of letters in the Persian alphabet to 31. G&acirc;f would bring it to 32.  </p>
	
	<p>In Turkish Peh was a particularly useful development, because in Turkish, the instances of P accumulate: voiced consonants which occur at the end of a Turkish word will shift regularly to unvoiced ones, noticeable particularly with loan words (thus Ahmad becomes Ahmet).  Arabic <em>kit&acirc;b</em> (book) becomes <em>kitap</em>; Persian <em>shar&acirc;b</em> (wine) becomes <em>&#351;arap</em>. This gives Turkish an advantage with loan words: <em>palas</em> (palace), <em>petrol</em> (gasoline), <em>protocol</em>, <em>pantolon</em> (Arabic <em>ban&#7789;&acirc;l&ucirc;n</em>), patates (Arabic <em>ba&#7789;&acirc;&#7789;is</em>).
	 
