	<h3>Power</h3>
	
	<p>The Persian word <em>pahlav&acirc;n</em>, &ldquo;hero,&rdquo; is one of those key terms which occupy the center of a culture &mdash; &ldquo;hero,&rdquo; suggesting bravery and dependability. Heroes of Ferdowsi&rsquo;s great 10th-century Persian epic, the <em>Sh&acirc;hn&acirc;meh</em>, get the epithet <em>pahlav&acirc;n</em>. It becomes in Arabic <em>bahlaw&acirc;n</em>. (The Persian V becomes Arabic W. The <em>-&acirc;n</em> changes as well: Persian <em>pahlav&acirc;n</em> rhymes with a long A, as in &ldquo;don,&rdquo; or &ldquo;brawn.&rdquo; Arabic <em>bahlaw&acirc;n</em> ends with a sharper A, rhyming with English &ldquo;van&rdquo; or &ldquo;bran.&rdquo;) And Persian P changes to Arabic B. Arabic <em>bahlaw&acirc;n</em> lost the elevated meaning of its predecessor: in Arabic it becomes a word for an acrobat or street performer (like the Anthony Quinn character in Fellini&rsquo;s <em>La Strada</em>). This decline has happened in more than one place. I am told that in Malayalam, a Dravidian language of south India, the language of Kerala, a <em>fayalvan</em> is a wrestler, tough guy in general, or a bouncer in a nightclub.</p>
	
	<p>A <em>pil</em> in Persian (pronounced &ldquo;peel&rdquo;) is an elephant. In Arabic, early on, it became <em>f&icirc;l</em> (pronounced &ldquo;feel&rdquo;). A <em>pil-tan</em>, an elephant body, is the epithet for a hero in the <em>Sh&acirc;h&acirc;meh</em>. (Elephants are often martial animals. The chess piece we know as the bishop was a <em>pil</em>.)</p>
	
	<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/pa-3.png" width="350" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>

	<p>Parthians (in contemporary Persian P&acirc;rt&icirc; or Ashk&acirc;n&icirc;, one of the empires which preceded the Sasanians) were famous for a distinctive military skill &mdash; twisting in the saddle to shoot an arrow behind, the opposite direction from where they were riding. It was called in English a Parthian shot, and only gradually became a &ldquo;parting shot.&rdquo;</p>
	
	<p><em>Pahlav&acirc;n</em> is related etymologically to &ldquo;Parthian.&rdquo; The same is true of &ldquo;Pahlavi,&rdquo; a term for the language we call Middle Persian, the pre-Islamic language spoken in the Sasanian empire. The language Pahlavi is valued in Iran as the expression of a purer Persian, before Arabic loan words arrived, but it is valued as seen from a distance. It isn&rsquo;t treated with the same hands-on reverence we accord to Latin and Greek in a European or American education, where, at the time of writing, the languages may still be taught. We experience them in legal and medical terminology. We can dot our conversation with Latin to make a point or perhaps just to sound learned. The language Pahlavi is not taught in Iranian high schools, even if the histories of Cyrus (Kurosh, or S&icirc;ruz, founder of the Achaemenid empire) and Darius (Dary&ucirc;sh, 5th century BCE) are examples of a revered past, which still exist as given names, even in Europe and America.</p>
	
	<p>A quatrain of Omar Khayyam (not one of the famous ones) imagines the nightingale, following tradition, speaking to the rose in Pahlavi:
	 
	<p><blockquote>Bolbol be-zab&acirc;n-e Pahlav&icirc; b&acirc; gol-e zard<br>
	Fary&acirc;d ham&icirc;-zanad keh may b&acirc;yad khord.</blockquote></p>
	 
	<p><blockquote>[The nightingale calls out to the yellow rose, in Pahlevi, &ldquo;you must drink wine.&rdquo; (FitzGerald translates &ldquo;. . . in divine /High-piping Pehlevi, with &ldquo;Wine! Wine! Wine!&rdquo;&mdash;The Nightingale cries to the Rose . . .&rdquo; Quatrain vi, 1st edition)]</p></blockquote>
	
	<div class="illo"><img src="../_img/pa-9.png" width="500" /></div>

	<p>I can&rsquo;t think of a logical reason for the nightingale to know Pahlavi, unless to make that point that wine was not prohibited before Islam. I can&rsquo;t determine whether it is a positive reference or a neutral one. I couldn&rsquo;t say why the rose is yellow either.</p>
	
	<p>The term Pahlavi was appropriated by Reza Shah, in the 1930s, as the name for his ill-fated dynasty, the dynasty that met its end a half-century later, in 1979. Pahlavi was one of many Peh words linked to kingship and power. The <em>p&acirc;d</em> in English &ldquo;padishah,&rdquo; for instance, develops from an old Persian term for potency and protection (<em>patakh</em>, from an Indo-European stem <em>poti</em>, cognates of English &ldquo;potency,&rdquo; &ldquo;potential,&rdquo; &ldquo;potentate,&rdquo; and &ldquo;power&rdquo;).</p>
	
	<p><em>P&acirc;d</em>, by a circuitous route, gives us in English &ldquo;bezoar,&rdquo; the word for an ugly hard mass found in the stomachs of ruminant animals, for some reason valued as an antidote for poisons. The word &ldquo;bezoar&rdquo; appears in English dictionaries, but it has a borrowed look. Between <em>p&acirc;d</em> and bezoar (from P word to B word) you hear the sign of a passage through the Arabic-speaking world. The same <em>p&acirc;d</em> in the sense of &ldquo;protection against" survives in modern Persian only as a prefix, as with the word <em>zahr</em>, &ldquo;poison,&rdquo; thus <em>p&acirc;d-zahr</em>, protection against poison, an antidote.</p>
	
	<p>Peh words for power and kingship are not rare. Turkish <em>Pa&#351;a</em>, pronounced &ldquo;pasha,&rdquo; the highest title of civilian officials in the Ottoman empire, is a Turkish variant of Persian <em>p&acirc;dish&acirc;h</em>. What we called the <em>sublime porte</em> (the <em>b&acirc;b al-&lsquo;&acirc;li</em>, the high gate), was in Turkish the <em>pa&#351;a kap&#305;s&#305;</em>, the pasha's gate. A <em>p&acirc;</em> in Persian is a foot or leg, a <em>p&acirc;shneh</em> a heel. <em>P&acirc;shneh-ye &acirc;hen</em> is the title in Persian of Jack London's <em>The Iron Heel</em>. <em>P&acirc;band</em> means fetters. <em>P&acirc;-bus</em> is kissing the feet.
	 
