	<h3>Yankee Hafez</h3>
	
	<p>There is a short poem by Ralph Waldo Emerson, published in 1847, in the form of a dialogue between the poet and the sky. </p>
	
	<p><blockquote>I said to heaven that glowed above,<br/>
	O hide yon sun-filled zone,<br/>
	Hide all the stars you boast;<br/>
	For, in the world of love<br/>
	And estimation true,<br/>
	The heaped-up harvest of the moon<br/>
	Is worth one barley-corn at most,<br/>
	The Pleiads' sheaf but two.</blockquote></p>
	
	<p>It&rsquo;s an awkward poem, at least to a contemporary reader, but the theme is pretty clear. He&rsquo;s describing the sky in the terms you might use for an American farm. The moon has a harvest. (After all, sometimes it can look like a sickle.) The Pleiades is a sheaf of barley, and consequently love, bigger than all of them, is its own universe.</p>

	<p>Emerson is imitating, via a German translation by Baron Joseph von Hammer Purgstall, a handful of lines from a poem by the great Persian poet Hafez. (It was in von Hammer&rsquo;s translations from Persian that Goethe found the source for his <em>West-East Divan</em>.) The Yankee bluntness which imagines an intimate conversation with the sky has a counterpart in Hafez&rsquo;s Persian, but the Persian text operates on a bigger scale. It&rsquo;s longer and subtler; it builds gradually, a miniature narrative which begins with the poet looking at the sky, chastened by the big vista.</p>

	<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/pa-7.png" width="300" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>

	<p><blockquote>&#1605;&#1586;&#1585;&#1593; &#1587;&#1576;&#1586; &#1601;&#1604;&#1705; &#1583;&#1740;&#1583;&#1605; &#1608; &#1583;&#1575;&#1587; &#1605;&#1607; &#1606;&#1608;<br/>
	&#1740;&#1575;&#1583;&#1605; &#1575;&#1586; &#1705;&#1588;&#1578;&#1607; &#1740; &#1582;&#1608;&#1740;&#1588; &#1570;&#1605;&#1583; &#1608; &#1607;&#1606;&#1711;&#1575;&#1605; &#1583;&#1585;&#1608;</blockquote></p>
	
	<p><blockquote>Mazra&lsquo;- e sabz-e falak didam-o d&acirc;s-e mah-e now<br/>
	Y&acirc;dam az keshteh-ye kheish &acirc;mad-o hang&acirc;m darow.<br/></blockquote>
	
	<blockquote><p>[&ldquo;I saw the green fields of the sky and the crescent moon's sickle; it made me think of my own farming and, with it, to think of harvest.&rdquo; (In Dick Davis&rsquo;s translation:<br/>
	I saw the green fields of the sky<br/>
	and there a sickle moon&mdash;<br/>
	I reckoned what I&rsquo;d sown, and thought,<br/>
	&ldquo;The harvest will come soon.&rdquo;)]</p></blockquote>
	 
	<p>The two layers of the poem &mdash; sky (<em>falak</em>) and field (<em>mazra&lsquo;</em>, i.e. the speaker&rsquo;s figure for his own life, his career, soul, his looming mortality) &mdash; come together for Hafez in an effortless gesture. (The transition from sky to field is easier in Persian, where the sky can be described as green.)</p>
	
	<p>Hafez thinks of his own unharvested fields and reproaches his fate. A voice, presumably from the sky, replies with reassuring advice. Six of the poem&rsquo;s eight <em>bayts</em> are what that voice tells him. If you remain chaste and pure (<em>p&acirc;k</em>), like <em>mas&icirc;&#7717;</em> (&ldquo;messiah,&rdquo; Jesus), your lamp will take on cosmic brightness: &ldquo;K&rsquo;az cher&acirc;gh-e tow be-khorsh&icirc;d rasad &#7779;ad partow,&rdquo; &ldquo;from your lamp, the sun will gather a hundred <em>partow</em>, rays of light.&rdquo; That partow could be the center of the poem. A partow is in context a faint light (a little light which can grow, as in &ldquo;this little light of mine&rdquo;). The picture of an oil-lamp&rsquo;s faint, earthly light, challenging the biggest light of all, sums up the poem.</p>
	
	<p>Peh words in Persian often convey a theme of paleness, passivity, delicacy: <em>par</em> (&ldquo;feather&rdquo;), <em>parh&icirc;z</em> (&ldquo;abstinence&rdquo;), <em>p&acirc;varch&icirc;n</em> (&ldquo;on tiptoe&rdquo;), <em>par&icirc;deh</em> (&ldquo;pale&rdquo;), <em>parv&acirc;neh</em> (&ldquo;butterfly&rdquo;), <em>par&acirc;kandan</em> ("to scatter&rdquo;), <em>p&acirc;reh</em> (&ldquo;torn, worn out, ragged&rdquo;), Turkish <em>p&acirc;muk</em> or Persian <em>panbeh</em> (&ldquo;cotton&rdquo;), <em>pari</em> (&ldquo;fairy&rdquo;). An object which stirs the wind, a <em>pankeh</em>, is a fan, Anglo-Indian &ldquo;punkah.&rdquo; An object stirred by the wind, a <em>pardeh</em>, is in Persian a curtain. In the form <em>purdah</em>, it refers to the whole social system which requires the social separation, the curtain between men and women. (Then again, we remember that a <em>pil</em> is an elephant.)</p>
	
	<p>Hafez&rsquo;s image of his earthly <em>partow</em> outshining the heavens is not out of key conceptually with the New England farm conjured up in Emerson's version. The <em>bayt</em> from Hafez&rsquo;s ghazal which appealed to Emerson most is easy to spot:</p>
	
	<p><blockquote>&#1570;&#1587;&#1605;&#1575;&#1606; &#1711;&#1608; &#1605;&#1601;&#1585;&#1608;&#1588; &#1575;&#1740;&#1606; &#1593;&#1592;&#1605;&#1578; &#1705;&#1575;&#1606;&#1583;&#1585; &#1593;&#1588;&#1602;<br/>
	&#1582;&#1585;&#1605;&#1606; &#1605;&#1607; &#1576;&#1580;&#1608;&#1740; &#1582;&#1608;&#1588;&#1607; &#1740; &#1662;&#1585;&#1740;&#1606; &#1576;&#1583;&#1608;&#1580;&#1608;</blockquote></p>
	
	<p><blockquote>sm&acirc;n gu ma-forush &icirc;n &lsquo;azmat k'andar-e &lsquo;eshq<br/>
	Kharman-e mah be-ju-ye khushe-ye Parvin be-dow ju.</blockquote></p>
	
	<p><blockquote>[&ldquo;Tell the sky `don't be proud of all that grandeur,' because in the realm of love, the weight of the moon sells for a grain of barley (we might say &lsquo;for peanuts&rsquo;&rdquo;) the cluster of stars called Parvin sells for two."  Dick Davis translates:</blockquote></p>
	
	<p><blockquote>Say to the heavens, &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t boast of splendor!&rdquo;<br/>
	When love is matched with you,<br/>
	The harvest of the moon&rsquo;s a grain,<br/>
	and of the stars but two. &mdash;36]</blockquote></p>
	 
	<p>Parv&icirc;n, the Pleiades, is a cluster of faint stars. Parvin can be called a <em>khusheh</em> (common word for an ear of corn, or a cluster of grapes). So the sky is just another farm. And the farm is Hafez&rsquo;s career. And his career can overwhelm the sky. Hafez is fond of shifts in scale, the larger the imbalance the better. In the farmers&rsquo; market of love, both the moon and the Pleiades are worth very little. 
	 
	<h3>Chess</h3>
	
	<p>So feeling, emotion, love, is greater than anything we can name. Something small which contains something bigger is for Hafez another characteristic shift of scale. In the same poem, the same encouraging voice tells Hafez that something so small as the beauty spot on a beautiful cheek, a <em>kh&acirc;l</em>, can have big aspirations. The scene is a battlefield, also the battlefield of love, and, at the same time, a chessboard. The <em>kh&acirc;l</em> is a player:</p>
	
	<p><blockquote>&#1576;&#1740;&#1583;&#1602;&#1740; &#1585;&#1575;&#1606;&#1583; &#1705;&#1607; &#1576;&#1585;&#1583; &#1575;&#1586; &#1605;&#1607; &#1608; &#1582;&#1608;&#1585;&#1588;&#1740;&#1583; &#1711;&#1585;&#1608;</blockquote></p>

	<p><blockquote>[B&icirc;daq&icirc; r&acirc;nd keh bord az mah-o khursh&icirc;d gerow]</blockquote></p>
	 
	<p>On the chessboard of love the <em>kh&acirc;l</em>, the beauty spot, plays a pawn, a <em>b&icirc;daq</em>, which overcomes, or harvests, the sun and moon. Pawns, if they reach the other side of the board, metamorphose from the least to the most powerful piece in the game. The <em>b&icirc;daq</em> becomes the piece called the <em>Vaz&icirc;r</em>, the minister or advisor to the king, the piece we call the Queen. It&rsquo;s a battlefield promotion, from foot soldier to a figure of power of court, to a being which controls the sky.</p>
	
	<p>The English word &ldquo;pawn&rdquo; traces back to Latin <em>pedes</em>, &ldquo;foot soldier,&rdquo; from the same stem as Persian <em>p&acirc;</em>, &ldquo;foot.&rdquo; The word for a foot soldier in Persian, which is also the word for a pawn, is <em>piy&acirc;deh</em>, which evolves from the same stem. Hafez, however, uses a different term, the synonym <em>b&icirc;daq</em>.</p>
	
	<p><em>Bidaq</em> is in a way not just a synonym, but the same word. When <em>piy&acirc;deh</em> became a loan word in Arabic, the P became a B. The <em>-eh</em> ending, for complicated reasons, became <em>-aq</em>. (The Arabic plural of <em>b&icirc;daq</em> is <em>bay&acirc;daq</em>, which is a bit more recognizable as a variant of piy&acirc;deh.) So when Persian speakers turned to Arabic to find a synonym for <em>piy&acirc;deh</em>, what they found was <em>b&icirc;daq</em>, which by now looked different enough to be a different word. And so <em>piy&acirc;deh</em> leaves the medium of Persian for the Arab world and comes back to Persian as a loan word. A foot soldier goes overseas and comes back changed.</p>
	
